    <subsection xml:id="subsec-construction-of-parallel-lines">
        <title>Construction of parallel lines</title>
        <p>
            Parallel lines are lines that are the same distance apart from each other and they will never meet. 
        </p>
    
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription>Parallel lines</shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="parallel-lines">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw[thick,red] (-2,0) node[left] {$A$} -- (3,0) node[right]{$B$};
                    \draw[thick,blue,shift={(60:2cm)}] (-3,0) node[left] {$C$} -- (2,0) node[right]{$D$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>

        <p>
            Lines <m>AB</m> and <m>CD</m> are parallel.
        </p>
        <activity>
            <p>
                Here ia an activity from <em>Math Open Reference</em> on how to construct a parallel lines using a pair of compasses and a ruler.
            </p>
            <p>
                Click on the link:<url href="https://www.mathopenref.com/constparallel.html" /> to access the activity.
            </p>
        </activity>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                In the exercise below, you are provided with a GeoGebra applet. You are required to construct parallel lines.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Using the <term>point tool(window 2)</term> in the toolbar, create two points <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>line tool(window 3),</term> create a line passing through the points <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>point tool(window 2),</term> create another point <m>C</m> on the applet.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>parallel line tool(window 4),</term> create a line, parallel to <m>AB</m> and passing through point <m>C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>move tool(window 1),</term> drag points  <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> and observe what happens to the line passing through point <m>C.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Parallel lines</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Parallel-lines" platform="geogebra" width="95%" aspect="4:3">
